    "reasoning": "The requirement is to implement a combinational circuit module named `TopModule` with two single-bit inputs (`a`, `b`) and seven single-bit outputs. Each output must implement a specific logic function based on the inputs:\n1. `out_and`: $a \text{ AND } b$\n2. `out_or`: $a \text{ OR } b$\n3. `out_xor`: $a \text{ XOR } b$\n4. `out_nand`: $\text{NOT} (a \text{ AND } b)$\n5. `out_nor`: $\text{NOT} (a \text{ OR } b)$\n6. `out_xnor`: $a \text{ XNOR } b$\n7. `out_anotb`: $a \text{ AND NOT } b$ (i.e., $a \text{ AND } \text{NOT } b$)\n\nSince all logic is combinational and the interface is fixed, the most straightforward and synthesizable way to implement this is using continuous `assign` statements. This adheres to the requirement that sequential logic without reset should be initialized in an initial block (though not necessary for pure combinational logic, it's good practice for clarity if signals were internal). We will use `logic` for all ports and internal signals as per the instructions.\n\n**Advice to avoid syntax errors:**\n1. **Port Declaration:** Ensure the module definition exactly matches the interface provided, using `logic` for all ports.\n2. **Gate Implementation:** For combinational logic, `assign` statements are preferred over `always @(*)` blocks for simple gate implementations like these, as they are cleaner and directly map to hardware gates.\n3. **NAND/NOR/XNOR:** Remember the definitions: NAND is the negation of AND, NOR is the negation of OR, and XNOR is the negation of XOR.\n4. **Specific Logic (`out_anotb`):** `a AND NOT b` translates directly to `a & ~b`.\n\nI will use direct assignment statements for maximum clarity and adherence to combinational design practices.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic a,\n    input  logic b,\n    output logic out_and,\n    output logic out_or,\n    output logic out_xor,\n    output logic out_nand,\n    output logic out_nor,\n    output logic out_xnor,\n    output logic out_anotb\n);\n\n    // (1) out_and: a and b\n    assign out_and = a & b;\n\n    // (2) out_or: a or b\n    assign out_or = a | b;\n\n    // (3) out_xor: a xor b\n    assign out_xor = a ^ b;\n\n    // (4) out_nand: a nand b (NOT (a AND b))\n    assign out_nand = ~(a & b);\n\n    // (5) out_nor: a nor b (NOT (a OR b))\n    assign out_nor = ~(a | b);\n\n    // (6) out_xnor: a xnor b (Equivalent to a == b)\n    assign out_xnor = ~(a ^ b);\n\n    // (7) out_anotb: a and-not b (a AND NOT b)\n    assign out_anotb = a & ~b;\n\nendmodule"
